📊 Model Performance Summary

This section summarises the quantitative results obtained across morphometric analysis, classical machine learning, deep learning, graph-based modelling, and expert evaluation for the classification of Reactive Follicular Hyperplasia (RFH) and Follicular Lymphoma (FL).

🧩 Morphometric Analysis
Quantitative nuclear morphometry revealed statistically significant differences between RFH and FL:
Follicular Lymphoma (FL) nuclei exhibited:
Larger nuclear area (p < 0.0051)
Greater nuclear perimeter (p < 0.0105)
Higher eccentricity (p < 0.0001), consistent with irregular nuclear morphology

Reactive Follicular Hyperplasia (RFH) nuclei showed:
Higher nuclear circularity (p < 0.0026), indicating more regular nuclear contours
Mean optical density (OD):
No statistically significant difference (p > 0.1614)

📌 These findings demonstrate a clear morphometric separation between benign and malignant follicular lesions (Figure 2).
🧮 Traditional Machine Learning (XGBoost)
An XGBoost classifier integrating clinicopathological and morphometric variables achieved:
Accuracy: 0.788
ROC AUC: 0.904
F1-score: 0.741
Precision: 0.909
Recall: 0.625

